This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with natural language semantics. It could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as it proposes a way to ground semantics in a strongly typed ontology, which is a common approach in AI. Additionally, the paper's focus on commonsense reasoning and ontology aligns with the interests of the cs.LG (Machine Learning) community. The paper's discussion of the triviality of natural language phenomena could also make it relevant to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) community, as it could have implications for natural language processing in security contexts. Finally, the paper's emphasis on compositional semantics could make it relevant to the cs.PL (Programming Languages) community, as compositional semantics is a key concept in programming language theory.
